The '''''Deutschland'' class''' was a group of five [[pre-dreadnought battleship]]s built for the German [[Kaiserliche Marine]]. The class comprised {{SMS|Deutschland|1904|2}}, {{SMS|Hannover||2}}, {{SMS|Pommern||2}}, {{SMS|Schlesien||2}}, and {{SMS|Schleswig-Holstein||2}}. Built between 1903 and 1908, the ships closely resembled those of the preceding {{sclass-|Braunschweig|battleship|4}}, though they had stronger armor protection. They were made obsolete before they were even completed by the launch of the revolutionary [[Royal Navy]] battleship {{HMS|Dreadnought|1906|6}} in 1906. As a result, they were the last ships of that type built for the German Navy. They were followed by the {{sclass-|Nassau|battleship|1}}s, Germany's first [[dreadnought battleship]]s.

With the commissioning of the ''Deutschland'' class, the fleet had enough battleships to form two full battle squadrons; the fleet was then reorganized into the [[High Seas Fleet]], which saw combat during [[World War I]]. Despite their obsolescence, all five of these ships were present at the [[Battle of Jutland]] on 31 May – 1 June 1916. In the confused night actions, ''Pommern'' was torpedoed and sunk. After the battle, the four surviving ships were removed from the front-line fleet and employed in secondary tasks. The [[Treaty of Versailles]] permitted Germany to retain several old battleships for coastal defense, including the four ''Deutschland''-class ships.

However, instead of being used as a coastal defense ship, ''Deutschland'' was broken up in 1920–1922. ''Hannover'' was to be converted into a target vessel, although this was never done. She was eventually broken up in 1944–1946. ''Schlesien'' and ''Schleswig-Holstein'' were the only two vessels of the class to see continued front-line service in the [[Reichsmarine]] and later the [[Kriegsmarine]]. Both ships saw limited duty during [[World War II]], which was inaugurated by the firing of ''Schleswig-Holstein''{{'}}s main guns at the Polish fortress at [[Westerplatte]]. Near the end of the war the two ships were both sunk.

== Design ==

The five ''Deutschland''-class battleships were the last pre-dreadnoughts built by the German Navy. They were similar to the preceding ''Braunschweig''-class ships—''Deutschland'' was nearly identical, though the design was modified slightly after the lead ship was laid down. The four subsequent ships had a somewhat different boiler arrangement and slightly thicker armor compared to the ''Braunschweig''-class ships.{{sfn|Staff|p=5}} All five vessels of the ''Deutschland'' class dispensed with the turret mountings for the secondary {{convert|17|cm|in|sp=us|adj=on}} guns; all of these guns were mounted in [[casemate]]s in the hull. The ships were built despite rumors of the capabilities of the revolutionary {{HMS|Dreadnought|1906|6}} then under construction.{{sfn|Hore|p=69}} Admiral [[Alfred von Tirpitz]] insisted on their construction, since larger ships would have necessitated widening the [[Kiel Canal|Kaiser Wilhelm Canal]]. This would have put a prohibitive strain on the naval budget for the year.{{sfn|Gardiner & Gray|p=141}}

=== General characteristics ===
[[File:Deutschland class line-drawing.png|thumb|left|Line-drawing of the ''Deutschland'' class]]

The ''Deutschland''-class ships were {{convert|125.90|m|ftin|abbr=on}} [[length at the waterline|long at the waterline]] and {{convert|127.60|m|ftin|abbr=on}} [[length overall|overall]]. They had a [[beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|22.20|m|ftin|abbr=on}} and a [[draft (hull)|draft]] of {{convert|8.21|m|ftin|abbr=on}} forward. The ships were designed to [[Displacement (ship)|displace]] {{convert|13191|t|LT|sp=us|0}} with a standard load, and displaced up to {{convert|14218|t|LT|sp=us|0}} at full load.{{sfn|Gröner|p=21}} The ''Deutschland''-class ships' hulls were built with transverse and longitudinal steel frames. Steel hull plates were riveted to the structure created by the frames. The hull was split into twelve [[watertight compartment]]s, although ''Pommern'' had thirteen compartments. The hull included a [[double bottom]] that ran for 84&nbsp;percent of the length of the ship.{{sfn|Gröner|p=20}}

The ships handled less easily than the preceding ''Braunschweig''-class ships, though they suffered less marked [[weather helm]]. Their [[metacentric height]] was {{convert|.98|m|ftin|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Gröner|p=21}} The ships' crews numbered 35 officers and 708 enlisted men. When one of them was a squadron [[flagship]], the crew was augmented by 13 officers and 66 enlisted men; while serving as a second command ship, 2 officers and 23 enlisted men were added to her standard crew.{{sfn|Gröner|p=20}} After she became a training ship in 1935, ''Schlesien''{{'}}s crew consisted of 29 officers and 559 enlisted men, plus up to 214 cadets. ''Schleswig-Holstein'' differed somewhat; her crew as a training ship numbered 31 officers and 565 men and up to 175 [[sea cadets|cadets]]. ''Deutschland'' and her sisters carried a number of smaller vessels, including two picket boats, one admiral's barge, two [[Launch (boat)|launches]], one [[pinnace (ship's boat)|pinnace]], two [[Cutter (boat)|cutters]], two [[yawl]]s, and two [[dinghy|dinghies]].{{sfn|Gröner|p=21}}

=== Machinery ===

''Deutschland'' and her sisters were equipped with three-shaft [[Marine steam engine#Triple or multiple expansion|triple expansion steam engines]]. The ships had a single rudder and three screw propellers. The two outer propellers were three-bladed, and {{convert|4.80|m|ftin|abbr=on}} in diameter. The center screw had four blades and was {{convert|4.50|m|ftin|abbr=on}} in diameter.{{sfn|Gröner|pp=18–20}} Steam was supplied to the engines by twelve marine-type boilers, four for each engine, with the exception of ''Deutschland''.{{sfn|Gröner|p=20}} This ship was boilered as in ''Braunschweig'', with eight marine-type boilers and six cylindrical boilers.{{sfn|Gröner|pp=18–20}} ''Deutschland''{{'}}s engines were rated at {{convert|16000|PS|ihp kW|lk=on|abbr=on|0}}, while the other four ships' engines were rated at {{convert|17000|PS|ihp kW|lk=on|abbr=on|0}}. The design speed for all of the ships was {{convert|18|kn|link=on}}, though on trials all five ships exceeded the figure.{{sfn|Gröner|p=21}}

The ships were designed to carry {{convert|700|t|sp=us}} of coal, though additional spaces could be utilized as fuel storage, which increased fuel capacity to {{convert|1540|t|sp=us}}. This provided a maximum range of {{convert|4800|nmi|sp=us}} at a cruising speed of {{convert|10|kn}}.{{sfn|Gröner|p=21}} Electrical power was supplied from four turbo-generators that supplied {{convert|260|kW}} each at 110&nbsp;[[volts]].{{sfn|Gröner|p=20}}

=== Armament ===

[[File:Bundesarchiv DVM 10 Bild-23-61-38, "SMS Deutschland", vorderer Geschützturm.jpg|thumb|''Deutschland''{{'}}s forward main battery turret|alt=Two long gun barrels jut out of a wide, round gun turret aboard a warship; the deck is covered in heavy chains, winches, and cranes]]

The armament of the ''Deutschland'' class was nearly identical to that of the preceding ''Braunschweig'' class, although it was rearranged slightly and increased in number. The primary armament consisted of four [[28 cm SK L/40 gun|{{convert|28|cm|in|abbr=on}} SK L/40]]{{efn|name=gun nomenclature}} quick-firing guns in two twin [[Gun turret|turrets]], one forward and one to the rear of the main superstructure. The turrets were the Drh.L. C/01 model, which allowed elevation to 30° and depression to −5°. At maximum elevation, the guns could hit targets out to {{convert|18830|m|yd|abbr=on}}. The guns fired {{convert|240|kg|lb|abbr=on}} shells in both high-explosive and [[armor-piercing shot and shell|armor-piercing]] (AP) types. [[Muzzle velocity]] for both types of shells was 820&nbsp;m/s (2,690&nbsp;f/s). At a range of {{convert|12000|m|yd|abbr=on}}, the AP shells could penetrate armor plating up to {{convert|160|mm|in|abbr=on}} thick.{{sfn|NavWeaps (28 cm/40)}}

The secondary battery consisted of fourteen {{convert|17|cm|in|abbr=on}} guns mounted in casemates amidships. Five were emplaced in the top deck and two one deck higher in the superstructure on either side. The casemates allowed elevation to 22° and depression to −5°. At 22°, the guns could engage targets {{convert|14500|m|yd|abbr=on}}. Each gun was supplied with 130 armor-piercing shells, and [[rate of fire|fired at a rate]] of approximately 5 per minute. The guns had an arc of train of 160°.{{sfn|NavWeaps (17 cm/40)}}

The ships were armed with twenty-two {{convert|8.8|cm|in|abbr=on}} quick-firing guns in single mounts, which were manually operated. The guns fired {{convert|15.4|lb|kg|abbr=on}} high-explosive shells at up to 12 rounds per minute.{{sfn|Gröner|p=20}}{{sfn|Gardiner & Gray|p=140}} They were supplied with 140 shells each. The guns could hit targets out to {{convert|11000|m|yd|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|NavWeaps (8.8 cm/35)}}

=== Armor ===

The ''Deutschland''-class ships were equipped with [[Krupp cemented armor]].{{sfn|Gröner|p=20}} ''Deutschland'' had a slightly different arrangement in the [[belt armor]] and the citadel in the superstructure. ''Deutschland''{{'}}s belt was {{convert|225|mm|in|abbr=on}} at the waterline and tapered to {{convert|140|mm|in|abbr=on}} on the lower edge. Her sister ships' belts was increased in thickness to {{convert|240|mm|in|abbr=on}} at the waterline and down to {{convert|170|mm|in|abbr=on}} on the bottom edge. In ''Deutschland'', the citadel armor was {{convert|160|mm|in|abbr=on}} thick, while on the other four ships the armor was 170&nbsp;mm thick. All five ships had an armored deck that was {{convert|40|mm|in|abbr=on}} thick.{{sfn|Staff|p=6}}

The main battery gun turrets had armored sides that were {{convert|280|mm|in|abbr=on}} thick and roofs that were {{convert|50|mm|in|abbr=on}} thick. The [[barbette]]s that held the turrets were armored with {{convert|250|mm|in|abbr=on}} thick steel. The casemate guns were protected by {{convert|35|mm|in|abbr=on}} thick armor plating. Their forward [[conning tower]]s were protected by {{convert|300|mm|in|abbr=on}} on the sides, while the rear conning towers had {{convert|140|mm|in|abbr=on}} worth of armor.{{sfn|Staff|p=6}}

== Construction ==

''Deutschland'' was ordered for the German fleet under the contract designation "N."{{efn|name=provisional names}} She was laid down at the [[Germaniawerft]] dockyard in 1903, under construction number 109.{{sfn|Gröner|pp=20–21}} She was launched on 20 November 1904; once she left the stocks fitting out work commenced. This included the installation of the ship's armament, completion of the interior compartments, and the finishing of the superstructure. By mid 1906 work on the ship was finished. ''Deutschland'' was commissioned into the fleet on 3 August of that year.{{sfn|Gröner|p=22}} ''Hannover'' was ordered as "O" and laid down at the [[Kaiserliche Werft Wilhelmshaven]] in 1904.{{sfn|Gröner|pp=20–21}} She was launched on 29 September 1905 and commissioned on 1 October 1907.{{sfn|Gröner|p=22}}

''Pommern'' was laid down at the [[AG Vulcan]] dockyard in Stettin under the provisional name "P" in 1904.{{sfn|Gröner|pp=20–21}} She was launched on 2 December 1905 and commissioned into the fleet on 1 October 1907.{{sfn|Gröner|p=22}} In 1904, ''Schlesien'' was laid down at the [[Schichau-Werke]] in Danzig under the provisional name "R."{{sfn|Gröner|pp=20–21}} She was launched on 28 May 1906 and commissioned on 5 May 1908.{{sfn|Gröner|p=22}} ''Schleswig-Holstein'' was ordered from the Germaniawerft dockyard under the contract name "Q." Her keel was laid there in 1905.{{sfn|Gröner|pp=20–21}} Launched on 17 December 1906, ''Schleswig-Holstein'' was completed by July 1908 and commissioned on the 6th, the last ship of the five to join the fleet.{{sfn|Gröner|p=22}}

